name: Bruce Fenton
tweet: One of the key bottlenecks in this process is the ledgers ‚Äî in the US the ledger saying which custodian broker owns what stocks is run by DTCC - brokers in turn run their own ledgers saying which client owns what   The current system relies on trusted third parties

name: Bruce Fenton
tweet: @HODLingOnward Yes there is a Byzantine generals dilemma - the various parties who have parts of the ledger saying who owns what stocks do not trust each other so they have to use a trusted third party to say what‚Äôs true.   Research DTCC and how clearing, custody, brokers & ledgers work.

name: Bruce Fenton
tweet: If a Coinbase shareholder wants to sell & buy #Bitcoin they must:  Open a brokerage account Transfer in the shares Sell Wait T+2 days for settlement (closed weekends) Request a wire to their bank account Wire the money back into Coinbase Wait for the wire to clear Buy #Bitcoin

name: Bruce Fenton
tweet: A Coinbase (COIN) stock holder who sold to take profits at the open & buy #Bitcoin still won‚Äôt have access to their money until a minimum of 2-3 days from now.  This is due to T+2 settlement combined with slow wires & legacy procedures.  Distributed ledgers for stocks solve this.
